        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>12 Upper Gower St</placeName>
                    <date>Thursday</date>
                    <salute>My dear M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Herbert</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am very much obliged to you for so quickly sending me M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Mears answer— it has destroyed some pleasant castles in airs—but house-hunters are doomed to suffer the greatest misfortunes &amp; ought to be the most patient of men.— It is very obliging of M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Mears’ being willing to bear my wishes regarding a house in mind.— Should Herbert <hi rend="underline">chance</hi> to have any further communication, it would be worth while to inform him, that I consider five miles from a Railway Station as the length of my tether.</p>
<p>With many thanks believe me dear M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Herbert | Yours very truly | C. Darwin</p>
<p>My wife left me on Tuesday with children for Staffordshire<ref target="#foot.f1"/> so that in the language of Boz<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I am a widow &amp; an orphan.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">On Tuesday, 3 May 1842, Emma travelled to Maer (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2337.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Emma Darwin</hi> (1904)</ref> 2: 36).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1313.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Charles Dickens</ref>’ <hi rend="italic">Sketches by ‘Boz’</hi>.</note>
        </div>        
            
